(4) Six (6) individuals appointed by the speaker of the senate; and
(5) Six (6) individuals appointed by the speaker of the house of
representatives.
(c) The task force members appointed pursuant to subdivisions (b)(4) and (5)
must be individuals who have expertise in the subject of solid waste or a subject related
to one (1) or more processes for the disposition of solid waste.
(d) Appointments to the task force must be made within thirty (30) days of the
effective date of this act. The terms of all appointed members of the task force begin
upon appointment to the task force and expire June 30, 2029. The governor's term must
coincide with the governor's term of office. The terms of legislative members of the task
force continue so long as such persons continue to be members of the general assembly
and chairs of their respective committees.
(e) An appointed member of the task force is subject to removal from the task
force for cause by the member's appointing authority. If an appointed member ceases to
be a member of the task force, then the appointing authority shall appoint a successor to
complete the term.
(f) The chair of the energy, agriculture and natural resources committee of the
senate and the chair of the committee of the house of representatives with jurisdiction
over subject matters pertaining to solid waste disposal, or either chair's replacement,
shall serve as co-chairs of the task force.
(g) The co-chairs shall call all meetings of the task force.
(h) The task force may conduct hearings; receive input, either in writing or in a
hearing, from experts and the public; and coordinate with departments of the executive
branch.
